29/06/2010
ANKARA, Turkey -- Prime Minister Recep Tayyip Erdogan said on Monday (June 28th) that the government is ready to meet with main opposition leader Kemal Kilicdaroglu, as well as other political party leaders, including those not represented in parliament, to seek a common anti-terror approach.
Speaking at a press conference, Erdogan stressed that the government's approach is proactive rather than defencive.
Erdogan also mentioned a possible meeting with Devlet Bahceli, leader of the National Movement Party.
Meanwhile, Turkish warplanes bombed suspected targets of the terrorist Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK) in northern Iraq on Monday, according to the PKK and an official in Iraqi Kurdistan.
No information on casualties was provided.
Also Monday, Turkish soldiers killed two people and injured another in the southern province of Hatay after mistakenly assuming they were terrorists.
The two victims, both elderly, were in a field in the mountainous region, a known hideout for PKK members.
(Sabah, Vatan, AFP, Cumhurriyet, Milliyet - 29/06/10;
Hurriyet, Dogan - 28/06/10)
